52
00:03:17,529 --> 00:03:18,969
that will move those centerpieces.

53
00:03:19,669 --> 00:03:21,110
They're fixed relative to each other.

54
00:03:21,930 --> 00:03:24,370
Green will always be next to orange, will always be next to yellow.

55
00:03:25,450 --> 00:03:28,031
And so the only thing we actually have to do to solve the cube

56
00:03:28,891 --> 00:03:31,512
is get these edge pieces and these corner pieces in the right place.

57
00:03:34,415 --> 00:03:37,298
In each one, they already have an identified place they should be.

58
00:03:37,338 --> 00:03:39,459
So if we look at this edge piece here, it has two stickers.

59
00:03:39,499 --> 00:03:40,780
It has green and it has yellow.

60
00:03:40,820 --> 00:03:44,042
So it must go between the green center and the yellow center.

61
00:03:44,062 --> 00:03:45,243
So it must go exactly here.

62
00:03:45,663 --> 00:03:47,305
There's only one piece that can go in that slot,

63
00:03:47,325 --> 00:03:49,486
and there's only one slot for that piece to go into.

64
00:03:50,327 --> 00:03:51,147
Same with the corner piece.

65
00:03:51,607 --> 00:03:53,628
It has three stickers, we can see it's got green and orange,

66
00:03:53,888 --> 00:03:55,909
so it must go between these green and orange centers.

67
00:03:56,429 --> 00:03:59,090
We see it's also got white, but this is the yellow face,

68
00:03:59,830 --> 00:04:01,871
so we can intuit that white must be on the bottom here,

69
00:04:02,211 --> 00:04:04,432
and this corner piece must go here into this slot.

70
00:04:06,433 --> 00:04:09,674
And then we're simply going to solve it layer by layer.

71
00:04:10,534 --> 00:04:13,955
So when you solve the first layer of a cube, it looks a bit like this.

72
00:04:13,995 --> 00:04:17,277
You can see those, because we've solved pieces instead of stickers,

73
00:04:17,337 --> 00:04:18,777
you can see those sides of the cube.

74
00:04:19,688 --> 00:04:21,228
at that satisfying T shape to them.

75
00:04:22,549 --> 00:04:26,250
And most people, given enough time, can intuit how to do this step on their own.

76
00:04:27,831 --> 00:04:31,712
The second stage is to move the middle pieces down into the...

77
00:04:31,972 --> 00:04:33,233
the edge pieces down into the middle layer.

78
00:04:33,253 --> 00:04:36,134
And you can see there's only four of them that have to go in to complete that.

79
00:04:36,494 --> 00:04:37,714
Two-thirds of the cube are completed.

80
00:04:37,914 --> 00:04:40,915
And most people, given more time, can complete this second step.

81
00:04:42,100 --> 00:04:46,643
The last step is to correctly position and orientate all of the pieces in the last layer,

82
00:04:46,703 --> 00:04:50,785
which is incredibly difficult and has loads of edge cases and you have no scratch space

83
00:04:50,825 --> 00:04:51,386
to do it into.

84
00:04:52,286 --> 00:04:57,269
So if I were you and you were interested in getting a Rubik's Cube, I would try and intuit

85
00:04:57,309 --> 00:05:01,531
these first two steps and especially if you're interested more in speedcubing than anything

86
00:05:01,591 --> 00:05:05,854
else than the puzzle nature of it, then I would just skip the third step and look up

87
00:05:05,894 --> 00:05:06,254
a solution.

88
00:05:08,088 --> 00:05:13,933
But speedcubers aren't intuiting how to solve the cube every time they do a speed solve.

89
00:05:14,233 --> 00:05:14,914
I'm not doing that.

90
00:05:14,934 --> 00:05:17,016
I couldn't do that in 30 seconds.

91
00:05:18,297 --> 00:05:20,659
We're using several tools in order to get us to that step.

92
00:05:20,799 --> 00:05:22,460
And one of the first tools we're using is algorithms.

93
00:05:22,540 --> 00:05:25,863
So we're breaking the solve down into many individual steps.

94
00:05:25,883 --> 00:05:28,466
You've already seen some of them, first layer, middle layer, last layer.

95
00:05:28,486 --> 00:05:30,287
But then you can break it down even further.

96
00:05:30,933 --> 00:05:32,796
And so you recognize the current step you're on,

97
00:05:33,096 --> 00:05:34,798
you know the step you want to be on next,

98
00:05:35,279 --> 00:05:38,142
and then you will have memorized the exact moves,

99
00:05:38,182 --> 00:05:40,745
the exact turns that get you from this sub-step

100
00:05:40,785 --> 00:05:42,587
to the next sub-step, and that's called an algorithm.

101
00:05:42,787 --> 00:05:44,309
And it uses this notation you can see

102
00:05:44,349 --> 00:05:45,390
along the bottom of the slide here,

103
00:05:45,410 --> 00:05:47,192
which is just telling you exactly which face to turn

104
00:05:47,232 --> 00:05:48,053
and how far to turn it.

105
00:05:49,604 --> 00:05:53,867
And this algorithm we're looking at is taking that middle piece down and to the right.

106
00:05:53,887 --> 00:05:57,469
So when you have a piece on the top layer that you know needs to go down and to the

107
00:05:57,509 --> 00:06:01,031
right, you just execute these steps and it will be down and to the right and the rest

108
00:06:01,071 --> 00:06:02,131
of the cube won't be disturbed.

109
00:06:03,472 --> 00:06:04,573
So algorithms.

110
00:06:05,313 --> 00:06:06,134
You have to learn.

111
00:06:06,754 --> 00:06:11,156
A beginner probably needs to know half a dozen algorithms in order to finish the cube.

112
00:06:12,097 --> 00:06:16,119
The best speedcubers in the world will probably know hundreds of algorithms if not thousands

113
00:06:16,159 --> 00:06:16,640
of algorithms.

114
00:06:18,220 --> 00:06:21,641
And it's just about practice, repetition, like ingraining it in your memory.

115
00:06:23,141 --> 00:06:26,482
And then the next step is executing those algorithms really fast.

116
00:06:26,502 --> 00:06:28,162
This is called turns per second, or TPS.

117
00:06:28,222 --> 00:06:32,283
The best cubers will have upwards of ten, their solves will have upwards of ten turns

118
00:06:32,443 --> 00:06:33,163
in every second.

119
00:06:33,924 --> 00:06:38,205
And that's a matter of manipulating the cube in such a way that you don't have to re-grip

