236
00:12:22,130 --> 00:12:23,271
is just the internet.

237
00:12:24,351 --> 00:12:27,372
But once people started talking in IRC and in forums,

238
00:12:28,253 --> 00:12:31,854
then this notion of trying to run a world championship

239
00:12:31,874 --> 00:12:35,395
started growing, and trying to organize the sport as a sport

240
00:12:35,415 --> 00:12:36,215
rather than just a hobby.

241
00:12:37,267 --> 00:12:39,268
And it happened for the first time in 2003.

242
00:12:39,328 --> 00:12:43,472
They held the first of the modern Rubik's World

243
00:12:43,492 --> 00:12:45,093
Championships, Speedcubing World Championships.

244
00:12:45,113 --> 00:12:46,835
And it was run by this man on the right, Dan Gosby.

245
00:12:47,916 --> 00:12:51,919
And there were a fair number of teething troubles to do

246
00:12:51,999 --> 00:12:54,882
with running this event.

247
00:12:55,302 --> 00:12:55,402
And

248
00:12:56,493 --> 00:13:00,734
There was a fair amount of backlash, which is probably, in hindsight, entirely overblown,

249
00:13:01,515 --> 00:13:05,116
but still, Dan Gosby took this criticism rather personally,

250
00:13:05,216 --> 00:13:08,536
and he left the scene immediately after organizing this event.

251
00:13:09,657 --> 00:13:12,157
And this is an interesting inflection point in the history of speedcubing,

252
00:13:12,197 --> 00:13:16,618
because his style of world championship is very different to the world championship that we have today.

253
00:13:16,918 --> 00:13:20,339
It's very different to that average of five format that I've already shown you.

254
00:13:20,899 --> 00:13:24,120
He was much more interested in a much more confrontational...

255
00:13:24,860 --> 00:13:30,485
It's a television sport where there were mind games and it was much more like wrestling

256
00:13:30,525 --> 00:13:33,767
where you could even know if you weren't technically the best solver you could still win because

257
00:13:33,787 --> 00:13:35,148
you could get inside someone else's head.

258
00:13:35,909 --> 00:13:38,771
And that's very different to what we have these days so it's interesting to think about

259
00:13:38,811 --> 00:13:41,633
what the sport would be like if he had stayed around.

260
00:13:44,078 --> 00:13:47,340
So the next year, two people from the different sides of the world came together

261
00:13:48,440 --> 00:13:50,982
and decided they needed some kind of umbrella organization

262
00:13:51,502 --> 00:13:56,165
to help regulate the sport and organize events.

263
00:13:56,505 --> 00:14:00,708
And that was Tyson Mow on the left, who was part of the Californian speedcubing scene,

264
00:14:01,068 --> 00:14:03,789
and Ron Van Bucum on the right, who was part of the Netherlands scene.

265
00:14:04,230 --> 00:14:06,571
And they formed the WCA, the World Cube Association, in 2003.

266
00:14:06,631 --> 00:14:06,911
In 2004, sorry.

267
00:14:10,212 --> 00:14:15,396
And the next year they held their first WCA World Championship, which is weirdly hard

268
00:14:15,436 --> 00:14:18,878
to find good photos of, so you've got the really low-res rubbish stuff.

269
00:14:19,159 --> 00:14:20,380
And it was a success, people enjoyed it.

270
00:14:20,400 --> 00:14:25,303
It wasn't perfect, there were problems, but generally people had a good reaction to it,

271
00:14:25,423 --> 00:14:26,945
and then we were off to the races.

272
00:14:27,085 --> 00:14:29,406
Ever since, there was a World Championship every two years.

273
00:14:31,362 --> 00:14:35,484
So what did WCA do that, what did they bring to the table

274
00:14:36,104 --> 00:14:37,985
that helps improve the sport and the community?

275
00:14:39,025 --> 00:14:40,306
And I think there was a couple of factors here.

276
00:14:40,346 --> 00:14:43,707
The first is this aspect of consistency.

277
00:14:44,348 --> 00:14:47,109
So the Average of Five format that I've told you about

278
00:14:47,169 --> 00:14:49,410
is exactly the same at your local meetup.

279
00:14:49,950 --> 00:14:52,093
at your nationals and at the world championships.

280
00:14:52,494 --> 00:14:55,818
So it's very easy for you to attend any one of those levels

281
00:14:56,259 --> 00:14:59,142
and then move up or down the scale.

282
00:14:59,603 --> 00:15:00,885
It's very accessible to you to do that.

283
00:15:01,265 --> 00:15:02,827
And it's also very easy for the organizers

284
00:15:02,887 --> 00:15:04,730
because they've already run countless events

285
00:15:04,770 --> 00:15:05,691
of the exact same format.

286
00:15:05,731 --> 00:15:07,593
The only thing that changes is how many people are entering.

287
00:15:11,298 --> 00:15:14,059
They also have a very accessible format.

288
00:15:14,319 --> 00:15:18,080
So last year, Ralph Costa et al.

289
00:15:18,160 --> 00:15:21,700
published some work on trust spectrums,

290
00:15:22,200 --> 00:15:24,401
which they wanted to use to categorize

291
00:15:24,641 --> 00:15:25,861
MMO and online communities.

292
00:15:26,161 --> 00:15:27,421
But I think applies here as well.

293
00:15:28,421 --> 00:15:30,942
So Ralph Costa would categorize this as,

294
00:15:31,602 --> 00:15:34,982
speedcubing as a game with lots of parallel play,

295
00:15:35,182 --> 00:15:37,683
which means I can solve my Rubik's cubes

296
00:15:37,703 --> 00:15:38,783
and you can solve your Rubik's cubes

297
00:15:38,823 --> 00:15:40,183
and we don't really impact on each other.

298
00:15:40,984 --> 00:15:44,126
There are no what they called roles in this sport,

299
00:15:44,166 --> 00:15:48,330
which means I don't need to wait for someone to solve a 4x4 if I want to solve a 3x3.

300
00:15:49,030 --> 00:15:50,271
And they were independent resources.

301
00:15:50,732 --> 00:15:54,415
I can take as long or as slow as I want to solve my cubes,

302
00:15:54,575 --> 00:15:56,937
and you can take as long as you want, and we don't impact each other.

303
00:15:57,377 --> 00:15:58,719
And when you put all those together,

304
00:15:59,099 --> 00:16:03,102
they would categorize this sport as a low trust game, which sounds...

305
00:16:04,724 --> 00:16:07,585
divisive, but it's not. What it means is it's very, very accessible.

306
00:16:07,605 --> 00:16:12,548
It's very easy for someone to come along and join the sport, and it's very easy for people to start up their own

307
00:16:14,008 --> 00:16:20,792
their own events, because they don't need some minimum bar of quality player or some minimum quantity of people in order for it to happen.

308
00:16:21,472 --> 00:16:22,993
And I think that's vital. When you have,

309
00:16:23,874 --> 00:16:27,375
when you're starting with a puzzle that already has such a large learning curve,

310
00:16:28,416 --> 00:16:33,218
having a sport associated with it that actually has a really shallow learning curve helps balance that out.

311
00:16:36,149 --> 00:16:38,370
The WCA also has what they call the delegate system.

312
00:16:39,070 --> 00:16:44,232
And this means that any event anywhere in the world can be an official WCA event and

313
00:16:44,252 --> 00:16:48,013
can have official world records and official national records set at it as long as it has

314
00:16:48,053 --> 00:16:49,594
a WCA delegate in attendance.

315
00:16:49,694 --> 00:16:55,196
And that is someone who's trained in the WCA regulations as well as how to run a WCA event.

316
00:16:55,776 --> 00:16:59,597
Now the interesting thing is that any WCA delegate...

317
00:16:59,617 --> 00:17:00,458
Excuse me.

318
00:17:01,398 --> 00:17:02,999
can train another WCA delegate.

319
00:17:03,559 --> 00:17:05,580
So Ron Van Buchen, who you saw a few slides ago,

320
00:17:06,180 --> 00:17:08,841
used to fill his suitcase up with Rubik's Cubes,

321
00:17:09,341 --> 00:17:11,202
fly to some far-flung corner of the world

322
00:17:11,222 --> 00:17:12,382
where he knew there were some people

323
00:17:12,422 --> 00:17:13,523
interested in running events,

324
00:17:14,003 --> 00:17:16,103
train them as delegates, leave them with the cubes,

325
00:17:16,804 --> 00:17:18,164
and then within a year or two,

326
00:17:18,524 --> 00:17:19,985
that country was full of delegates

327
00:17:20,165 --> 00:17:21,746
trained to run events, and they were having

328
00:17:22,246 --> 00:17:25,007
like half a dozen events a year.

329
00:17:26,247 --> 00:17:29,048
So it helps it spread almost like a virus.

330
00:17:31,651 --> 00:17:35,154
And then finally, it's a very non-confrontational sport,

331
00:17:36,995 --> 00:17:39,918
as opposed to, like, Dan Gosby's model

332
00:17:39,958 --> 00:17:41,379
of a more wrestling-style sport.

333
00:17:42,660 --> 00:17:44,742
In fact, which is actually to its detriment

334
00:17:44,802 --> 00:17:46,143
in terms of a spectator sport,

335
00:17:46,343 --> 00:17:48,505
because if you're watching two people,

336
00:17:48,545 --> 00:17:49,526
and in the World Championships,

337
00:17:49,566 --> 00:17:51,747
they have the top two cubers on the stage,

338
00:17:52,048 --> 00:17:53,489
and they'll solve in turns.

339
00:17:53,529 --> 00:17:54,630
So one will do their first solve,

340
00:17:54,670 --> 00:17:55,731
the other one will do their first solve,

341
00:17:55,771 --> 00:17:57,792
the first one will do its second solve, and so on.

342
00:17:59,537 --> 00:18:03,102
But it's actually really hard for you as a spectator to work out who's in the lead right now,

343
00:18:03,142 --> 00:18:07,768
because you have to do all that mental arithmetic of throwing away the best and the worst and doing an average.

344
00:18:09,030 --> 00:18:12,515
So really all it comes down to is there's no strategic decision to make.

345
00:18:12,715 --> 00:18:15,499
Just make your next solve really fast. That's the only option.

346
00:18:16,707 --> 00:18:21,649
And that makes it very collegiate, it makes it very friendly, because all you're focused

347
00:18:21,669 --> 00:18:23,870
on is doing well and solving fast.

348
00:18:23,970 --> 00:18:29,472
And if someone beats you in an event, it doesn't really matter as long as you're pushing your

349
00:18:29,512 --> 00:18:30,512
personal best forward.

350
00:18:30,932 --> 00:18:34,353
And so everyone's really happy for everyone else as long as everyone's making progress.

351
00:18:35,033 --> 00:18:37,834
And it makes it a very friendly sport to be part of.

352
00:18:39,675 --> 00:18:40,655
So now we've got organization.

353
00:18:42,245 --> 00:18:50,012
What we need now is innovation so we can have more exciting, interesting things to do in

354
00:18:50,072 --> 00:18:50,392
a sport.

355
00:18:50,452 --> 00:18:56,097
And the major factor standing in the way of that at one point was the Rubik's Cube itself,

356
00:18:56,297 --> 00:19:03,002
the brand, the company behind it produced these cubes that are very good toys, but they're

357
00:19:03,062 --> 00:19:04,083
not good speed cubes.

358
00:19:04,223 --> 00:19:10,529
They're slow, they're inconsistent, they take ages to break in, they're very awkward to

359
00:19:10,709 --> 00:19:10,869
use.

360
00:19:13,018 --> 00:19:18,561
And I mentioned that the 2005, the WCA World Championships weren't perfect, and one of

361
00:19:18,581 --> 00:19:22,564
the things that wasn't perfect about it was that you had to use official brand, freshly

362
00:19:22,684 --> 00:19:24,925
unboxed Rubik's Cubes as part of the competition.

363
00:19:25,865 --> 00:19:30,488
And this was both unfair because people were getting, some people were getting cubes that

364
00:19:30,508 --> 00:19:33,890
were relatively easy to turn and some were getting ones that were hard to turn, but also

365
00:19:33,970 --> 00:19:34,711
unfair because...

366
00:19:35,850 --> 00:19:38,372
Licensed Rubik's Cubes vary from country to country.

367
00:19:38,412 --> 00:19:41,455
People coming from Japan, very used to a different color scheme,

368
00:19:41,715 --> 00:19:42,496
color scheme layout.

369
00:19:42,897 --> 00:19:45,179
And you can imagine that can make it very awkward to solve fast if

370
00:19:45,960 --> 00:19:47,301
white is no longer opposite yellow.

371
00:19:48,527 --> 00:19:50,209
And Tyson Marrow now says this was a mistake.

372
00:19:50,250 --> 00:19:53,273
He says, it's not the Nike 100 meters in the Olympics.

373
00:19:53,293 --> 00:19:54,835
It doesn't matter what trainers you're wearing.

374
00:19:55,276 --> 00:19:57,439
What matters is your time investment

375
00:19:57,479 --> 00:19:58,800
and your skill level and your talent.

376
00:19:59,321 --> 00:20:00,603
And so from that point onwards,

377
00:20:00,963 --> 00:20:02,505
the WCA have been very happy to take

378
00:20:03,466 --> 00:20:05,129
Rubik's brand sponsorship money,

379
00:20:05,269 --> 00:20:07,351
but you can use any cube you want in the competition.

380
00:20:08,878 --> 00:20:13,461
And so people started popping up, wanting to design better speedcubes for speedcubers.

381
00:20:14,081 --> 00:20:15,142
But they were still having trouble.

382
00:20:15,862 --> 00:20:19,985
If you remember, at the beginning of the talk, I said there was a billion cubes in the world,

383
00:20:20,065 --> 00:20:21,105
including counterfeits.

384
00:20:21,786 --> 00:20:25,488
And Seven Towns, which is the company that owns the Rubik's Cube brand, still has this

385
00:20:25,548 --> 00:20:26,608
hangover from the 80s of being very...

386
00:20:28,294 --> 00:20:31,517
very, very protective of Rubik's Cube and of counterfeit Rubik's Cubes.

387
00:20:31,877 --> 00:20:35,260
And they'll use things like patents and trademarks to try and stop people

388
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:38,282
selling what they think are counterfeit products.

389
00:20:38,582 --> 00:20:42,205
Unfortunately, speedcube designers often got caught in the crossfire of that.

390
00:20:42,946 --> 00:20:47,529
And so there was a stage in the mid-2010s where it's like good speedcubes were being

391
00:20:47,569 --> 00:20:52,213
sold flat-packed like this to try and avoid any implication that this was like an official Rubik's product.

392
00:20:53,606 --> 00:21:00,475
That eased up in the mid 2010s, and I'd love to do a whole talk about the patent-like cases

393
00:21:00,555 --> 00:21:04,921
and trademark cases and stuff, but I don't think that's a GDC talk that people would

394
00:21:04,941 --> 00:21:05,462
be interested in.

395
00:21:06,595 --> 00:21:10,176
But it eased up, and now these days there's a tremendous variety of different speedcubes

396
00:21:10,216 --> 00:21:13,337
and innovative designs in the market on making faster speedcubes.

397
00:21:13,417 --> 00:21:18,118
Things like having springs inside your cube that can make it more forgiving of bad turns,

398
00:21:18,498 --> 00:21:22,099
having magnets which make it more stable, having...

399
00:21:22,539 --> 00:21:27,420
Customization is the thing this last 12 months, of being able to set up the cube exactly how

400
00:21:27,480 --> 00:21:29,381
you want it, to make it your cube.

401
00:21:31,661 --> 00:21:33,243
But we're still not quite sustainable.

402
00:21:33,323 --> 00:21:34,445
So we've got innovation,

403
00:21:34,945 --> 00:21:36,808
but we haven't got sustainability yet.

404
00:21:36,908 --> 00:21:38,270
And this is because, like we said,

405
00:21:38,290 --> 00:21:41,494
there's maybe a million speedcubers in the world,

406
00:21:42,095 --> 00:21:44,998
but you can only really sell them one piece of plastic.

407
00:21:45,539 --> 00:21:47,381
And these pieces of plastic aren't that expensive.

408
00:21:48,042 --> 00:21:50,183
So to make it a sustainable business for the designers,

409
00:21:50,883 --> 00:21:52,684
what they need to do is sell you more plastic.

410
00:21:52,724 --> 00:21:54,825
And they can't sell you the Rubik's Cube because you already have a 3x3.

411
00:21:54,845 --> 00:21:58,527
So what they're going to do is manufacture different types of cubes

412
00:21:58,907 --> 00:22:00,227
and sell you those things instead.

413
00:22:00,728 --> 00:22:03,709
And that worked great, like that worked out great for speedcubers because...

414
00:22:05,120 --> 00:22:08,181
One thing they can never, they can always be pushing their times down and doing better

415
00:22:08,201 --> 00:22:11,862
and practicing more, but one thing they can never ever do is solve three by three for

416
00:22:11,882 --> 00:22:12,643
the first time again.

417
00:22:13,963 --> 00:22:19,185
And so getting these new puzzles, these new experiences is something they're very interested

418
00:22:19,205 --> 00:22:20,906
in and they're very happy to purchase these things.

419
00:22:21,426 --> 00:22:26,008
And so collecting as part of the hobby started, became a thing.

420
00:22:26,548 --> 00:22:28,809
And there's two main types of collecting.

421
00:22:29,970 --> 00:22:35,871
The first one is collecting as novelty, the idea of trying to have that first 3x3 experience again.

422
00:22:35,911 --> 00:22:41,633
And you can have that either as maybe adding more layers or more dimensions to your puzzle.

423
00:22:41,873 --> 00:22:46,094
So both of these kind of use 3x3 algorithms in a weird way.

424
00:22:47,135 --> 00:22:51,496
Or you can have something that's fundamentally different to the Rubik's Cube.

425
00:22:51,516 --> 00:22:53,816
This one on the left is called the square one,

426
00:22:53,836 --> 00:22:56,457
because it doesn't matter how many 3x3 algorithms you know,

427
00:22:56,797 --> 00:22:58,438
when you unbox it, you're back to square one.

428
00:23:01,974 --> 00:23:05,557
And there's also collection as aesthetic, the idea of collecting things that are interesting

429
00:23:05,617 --> 00:23:06,658
or rare or novel.

430
00:23:08,240 --> 00:23:11,923
And you've got things here, these are called shape mods, which are, these are both essentially

431
00:23:12,363 --> 00:23:13,004
Rubik's cubes.

432
00:23:14,707 --> 00:23:17,589
They're both 3x3s, except they've jumbled everything around.

433
00:23:17,609 --> 00:23:19,050
Where's my little laser pointer?

434
00:23:19,070 --> 00:23:23,493
So, this is actually the corner piece on the fissure cube,

435
00:23:23,853 --> 00:23:24,714
and this is the edge piece.

436
00:23:24,874 --> 00:23:26,175
So everything's slightly twisted.

437
00:23:26,515 --> 00:23:27,456
This is the ghost cube,

438
00:23:27,816 --> 00:23:30,098
which has every single piece has a unique shape.

439
00:23:30,178 --> 00:23:32,439
And see you're solving based on shape rather than position.

440
00:23:32,740 --> 00:23:33,220
But it's still a 3x3.

441
00:23:34,666 --> 00:23:35,547
And then there's things like this,

442
00:23:35,607 --> 00:23:37,929
which is the Oscar van Deveter sphere gear,

443
00:23:38,609 --> 00:23:39,870
which is really interesting to look at,

444
00:23:39,910 --> 00:23:42,372
really interesting to turn, but trivially easy to solve.

445
00:23:42,853 --> 00:23:45,175
No one's buying that because they want the experience

446
00:23:45,215 --> 00:23:45,955
of solving the puzzle.

447
00:23:45,975 --> 00:23:47,056
They're buying it because they think

448
00:23:47,076 --> 00:23:48,137
it looks cool on their shelf.

449
00:23:51,039 --> 00:23:54,502
So now we've got all the pillars I think we need

450
00:23:54,582 --> 00:23:58,666
for a sustainable sport, but no one joins your sport

451
00:23:58,726 --> 00:24:00,007
because they've heard that you've got

452
00:24:00,027 --> 00:24:00,947
good sustainable pillars.

453
00:24:02,059 --> 00:24:05,282
And so we need to get people in and I think there's two reasons why people

454
00:24:06,223 --> 00:24:11,107
get interested in join speedcubing. And the first one is definitely a novelty, a nostalgia factor.

455
00:24:12,648 --> 00:24:16,851
Because we talked about the beginning how everyone got burnt out on the Rubik's Cube in 82 and they

456
00:24:16,871 --> 00:24:21,455
couldn't solve it, but they didn't throw them away, they put them on their bookshelves. And so I can

457
00:24:21,475 --> 00:24:24,898
remember my parents' Rubik's Cube on their bookshelf, people younger than me can probably

458
00:24:24,938 --> 00:24:27,160
remember their grandparents' Rubik's Cube. And...

459
00:24:30,479 --> 00:24:33,521
We don't have that burnout from the original fad.

460
00:24:34,121 --> 00:24:38,804
And so for us, picking up a Rubik's Cube has got a huge dollop of nostalgia

461
00:24:39,024 --> 00:24:41,005
of the family home from when they were young.

462
00:24:41,645 --> 00:24:46,228
And I sent out some surveys to big speedcubing sites online

463
00:24:46,248 --> 00:24:48,850
to try and get some idea of how people got into speedcubing.

464
00:24:48,870 --> 00:24:51,051
I got some comments to back that up.

465
00:24:54,077 --> 00:25:01,381
But I think it's a really important part of the hobby itself, this nostalgia factor.

466
00:25:01,962 --> 00:25:07,265
And the other factor I think is important is this virality that comes with it as well.

467
00:25:07,325 --> 00:25:11,908
So this is a screenshot of a video of Colin Burns breaking the world record in 2015.

468
00:25:12,748 --> 00:25:16,371
And this is interesting because he was the first American to hold the world record for

469
00:25:16,391 --> 00:25:17,071
about a decade.

470
00:25:17,752 --> 00:25:21,894
Which means this clip went sort of viral on local news on the...

471
00:25:22,234 --> 00:25:22,475
